07683nam a22011655i 9780228013310DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280133107 a10.1515/97802280133102doi  a(DE-B1597)656008  a(OCoLC)1287825203  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aT752.B1b1967ebE97 2022eb 7aART0150402bisacsh04a907.4714/28qOCoLC223/eng/2023021600aExpo 67 and Its World :bStaging the Nation in the Crucible of Globalization /ced. by Steven Palmer, Craig Moyes. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b53 photos, 3 tables, colour insert  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Staging the Nation in the Crucible of Globalization -- tExpo 67 and Its (Laurentian) World -- tTwo Universal Endings: Architecture and Cinema at the New York and Montreal World's Fairs -- t“For We Have Waited a Hundred Thousand Years”: The Indians of Canada Pavilion and Indigenous Curatorial Practices -- tOur Two Masks: Canadian Colonial Humanism and Indigenous Representation at Montreal's World Exhibition -- tThe First Postcolonial World Exhibition: Revolutionary Cuba and the Black Atlantic at Expo 67 -- tInnovation and the Prospect of the Post-national in the Architecture of Expo 67 -- tMoving Image: Commissioned Quebec Cinema “à l'heure de l'Expo” -- tHere, There, and Everywhere: Youth Revolt in Quebec and around the World -- tGlass/Screen, or Dialectics at a (Momentary) Standstill: Marcelle Ferron's Windows at the International Trade Centre/Expo Club -- tStaging Modern Medicine in Montreal: Anatomy of an Avant-Garde Pavilion -- tThe New Brutalism and Design beyond Understanding at Expo 67 -- tSecret Agents at Expo: The Case of Kommissar X -- tEarth, River, (Is)Land: The Foundations and Re-foundations of Expo 67 -- tEpilogue “A Legend for Generations to Come”: Expo 67 in the Historical Memory of Contemporary Québécois -- tAppendix: Notes on Expo 67 Visitor Data -- tTables and Figures -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1967, Montreal hosted Man and His World/Terre des hommes. By far the most successful cultural event ever produced in Canada, it was embraced by the public at the same time as intellectuals from Marshall McLuhan to Umberto Eco hailed it as a new type of exhibition for a new global age.Because it was held where and when it was – on a man-made archipelago in the St Lawrence River seven years into Quebec’s Quiet Revolution – Expo 67 also provided a prism through which the idea of the nation could be refracted and recast in original ways. Misunderstood by some scholars as an expensive exercise in official patriotism, while maligned by Quebec intellectuals as a crypto-federalist distraction from the real business of national independence, the fair nevertheless showcased Montreal as the de facto capital of a suddenly modern Quebec engaging with a late-modern world.Expo 67 and Its World proposes a reappraisal of the 1967 Montreal International and Universal Exhibition across a range of political, social, and cultural spaces: from the dispossession of Indigenous Peoples and what was then known as the Third World, through the aspirations of Montreal, Quebec, and Canada, to the increasingly global ambit of youth culture, medicine, film, and finance. A new approach to understanding Expo 67, the collection challenges assumptions about the significance of the event to Canadian, Québécois, and First Nations history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExhibitionsxSocial aspectszQuébec (Province)zMontréal. 0aExhibitionsxSocial aspects